OL,6,FDefending, William Staunton appealed
OL,7,Ffor Hearldon to be spared from being
OL,8,Fsent to prison. He said Hearldon had
OL,9,Fsince found another job carrying out
OL,10,F'manual labour'.
OL,12,F"He is a grafter by nature," Mr
OL,13,FStaunton said. "He, on this occasion,
OL,14,Fhas stepped into the realm of the
OL,15,Fgrifter."
OL,17,FMr Staunton said that Hearldon was
OL,18,F'profoundly ashamed' of his behaviour.
